# -*- fill-column: 72 -*-
#+TITLE: Renting the Floor
#+SUBTITLE: India builds applications, not foundations. The gap with China is structural — a matter of conditions, not talent.
#+AUTHOR: gp
#+DATE: 2026-06-27

#+begin_quote
A note on method. This essay began with a hypothesis — that India does not
produce foundational systems software — and then sought evidence for it. That
order of operations carries a bias, and where evidence was ambiguous the
hypothesis got the benefit of the doubt. Quantitative claims are sourced in the
footnotes and current to mid-2026; market values in particular move daily, so the
premium argument in §1.3 is built to hold at the order-of-magnitude level, not on
any one day's price. The interpretive sections (§9, §10) and the five-mechanism
taxonomy (§7) are analytical models, not peer-reviewed findings. Corrections and
counter-evidence are welcome.
#+end_quote

Through 2026, the market judged India's software model. As AI began automating
the billable hour, the IT-services giants — TCS, Infosys, Wipro — shed a combined
₹8.5 lakh crore, the exchange's worst-hit sector.[fn:13] In the same months
Alibaba was re-rated up by roughly 70%, recast as an AI-and-cloud infrastructure
company.[fn:31] AI disintermediated the tenant and redefined the landlord — the
same technology, opposite outcomes, because one owned the floor it runs on and the
other rented it.

* 1. The Claim
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: claim
:END:

** 1.1 Two Kinds of Software
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: types
:END:

India is called a software nation. The title conflates two layers the industry
itself keeps apart.

| Layer | What it is | Examples |
|-------+------------+----------|
| Application | what a user touches | wallets, dashboards, ERP, SaaS |
| Middleware | the glue between apps and the floor | app frameworks, API gateways, ORMs |
| Systems / foundational | the floor everything runs on | OS, database, message broker, runtime |

Foundational software — /systems software/, in the trade — is the floor, and the
test for it is simple: /does other software depend on it?/ Whoever owns the floor
sets the terms for everyone above. India's headline numbers all measure the top
row. India is a tenant.

** 1.2 India's Champions Are All Application-Layer
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: champions
:END:

India's software giants are not technology companies in the Silicon Valley sense.
They are labour-cost arbitrage businesses that happen to run on code.

| Company | Revenue (FY25–26) | Employees | Model |
|---------+-------------------+-----------+-------|
| TCS | ~US$30B[fn:23] | 584,519[fn:14] | IT services, offshoring |
| Infosys | ~US$19.5B[fn:24] | 323,788[fn:14] | IT services, offshoring |
| HCLTech | ~US$13B[fn:26] | 223,000[fn:14] | IT services, offshoring |
| Wipro | ~US$10.4B[fn:25] | 233,232[fn:14] | IT services, offshoring |
| Tech Mahindra | ~US$6B[fn:27] | 148,000[fn:14] | IT services, offshoring |

The model is simple: Indian engineers at a fraction of Western cost. It is labour
arbitrage, not technology arbitrage — sector revenue per employee has sat near
US$50,000 across FY2020–FY2024.[fn:28] Three further measures confirm where the
value sits:

- /Patents./ TCS holds roughly 2,560 granted patents, most in process and
  methodology classes rather than core systems software; IBM holds on the order
  of 150,000 and Microsoft some 37,000 granted at the USPTO alone — a fifty-fold
  gap or more.[fn:1]
- /Products./ Few globally adopted software products originate in India; Tally,
  Freshworks, and Zoho are the exceptions, and all three sit at the application
  layer.
- /Open source./ Indian /companies/ have almost no corporate footprint in the
  Apache Foundation, the CNCF, or the Linux kernel. What contribution exists comes
  from individuals — most of them on American payrolls.

The success is real. It is application software and services, built on a floor
owned elsewhere.

** 1.3 The Foundational Premium: Market Value per Employee
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: premium
:END:

Owning the floor commands a structural valuation premium. Measured as market
value per employee, the firms that own foundational technology are worth two to
three /orders of magnitude/ more per head than the firms that rent it. India's
giants scaled headcount; they did not scale capital efficiency.

| Company | Market cap (mid-2026) | Employees | ~US$ / employee | Foundational output |
|---------+-----------------------+-----------+-----------------+---------------------|
| NVIDIA | ~$4.9T[fn:11] | 42,000[fn:12] | ~$115M | CUDA, GPU architecture[fn:15] |
| Apple | ~$4.6T[fn:11] | 166,000[fn:12] | ~$28M | Darwin/XNU, Swift[fn:16] |
| TSMC | ~$2.3T[fn:11] | 83,825[fn:12] | ~$27M | foundry process |
| Alphabet | ~$4.3T[fn:11] | 190,820[fn:12] | ~$23M | MapReduce, Kubernetes, Go[fn:18] |
| Meta | ~$1.5T[fn:11] | 78,865[fn:12] | ~$19M | React, Cassandra[fn:19] |
| Microsoft | ~$3.3T[fn:11] | 228,000[fn:12] | ~$14M | Windows NT, .NET[fn:17] |
| Alibaba | ~$314B[fn:11] | 123,711[fn:12] | ~$2.5M | OceanBase, RocketMQ[fn:21] |
| TCS | ~$90B[fn:13] | 584,519[fn:14] | ~$0.15M | — (services) |
| Infosys | ~$47B[fn:13] | 323,788[fn:14] | ~$0.15M | — (services) |
| Wipro | ~$20B[fn:13] | 233,232[fn:14] | ~$0.09M | — (services) |

The spread runs from roughly US$90,000 per employee at Wipro to over US$100M at
NVIDIA — a thousandfold or more. That gap is the foundational premium. The same
pattern holds for private and acquired firms: LinkedIn produced Apache
Kafka;[fn:20] ByteDance produced CloudWeGo and Monoio.[fn:22] And the premium is
not static in India's favour — through 2026 the market actively re-rated the
arbitrage model /downward/, with TCS, Infosys, and Wipro shedding a combined ₹8.5
lakh crore in value as AI began to erode the billable-hours business,[fn:13] the
thesis playing out in real time.

* 2. Is It a Talent Problem? No — a Surplus of the Average
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: talent
:END:

India hosts roughly 17 million developers on GitHub, a large share of the global
base.[fn:2] But ownership of the floor is measured by who /commits/ to
foundational open source, not who /uses/ it — and on that measure the share
collapses.

| Country | Developer share (approx) | Foundational-OSS contribution (author estimate) |
|---------+--------------------------+-------------------------------------------------|
| USA | ~18% | ~35% |
| China | ~16% | ~18% |
| India | ~17% | ~2% |
| UK | ~6% | ~6% |
| Germany | ~5% | ~5% |

The 2% figure for India is an author's estimate from Apache geographic patterns
and GitHub Innovation Graph active-user data, not a survey finding.[fn:29] The
direction, not the decimal, is the point: a near-equal share of the world's
developers, a near-absent share of its foundational commits.

This reframes the question entirely. Seventeen million developers producing not
one load-bearing database, kernel, or broker is not evidence of latent talent
waiting for better conditions — it is a /surplus of the average/. The size of the
cohort, set against the empty column, is the indictment, not the alibi. The
ecosystem manufactures volume, not depth. The rest of this essay asks what
produces depth, where China found it, and why India has not.

* 3. India's Foundational Software, Listed in Full
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: india-list
:END:

India has produced some foundational software. The list is short enough to print
in full — which is itself the finding.

| Project | Type | Origin | Licence | Scale |
|---------+------+--------+---------+-------|
| MOSIP | identity platform | IIIT-Bangalore, 2018 | MPL/MIT | ~26 countries, ~130M IDs[fn:3] |
| Frappe | application framework | 2009 | GPL | community in the tens of thousands[fn:9] |
| Listmonk | mailing-list manager | Zerodha | AGPL | used globally[fn:10] |
| DungBeetle | distributed SQL job server | Zerodha | open source | internal[fn:10] |
| kaf-relay | Kafka replication | Zerodha | open source | internal[fn:10] |
| Drove | container orchestrator | PhonePe | open source | ~350K cores, 3PB[fn:4] |
| Deluge | scripting language | Zoho | proprietary | runs the Zoho suite |
| WebNMS | network management | Zoho/AdventNet | proprietary | used by telecoms |

It is scattered, under-resourced, and frequently closed. It has not coalesced into
a stack. Contrast that, now, with a country where it did.

* 4. China's Stack
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: china-stack
:END:

China is in this argument as the control, not the rival. The organising driver was
/IOE-replacement/ — removing IBM (servers), Oracle (database), and EMC (storage)
once they became cost and supply-chain liabilities.[fn:5] Almost every major
project traces to the US incumbent it was built to displace.

| US incumbent | → | Chinese replacement |
|--------------+---+---------------------|
| Oracle | → | OceanBase |
| IBM MQ | → | RocketMQ |
| RHEL | → | openEuler |
| Envoy | → | MOSN |
| PostgreSQL | → | openGauss |

Unlike India's scattered list, this is a /stack/ — every layer filled, by name.

| Layer | Project | Origin | Licence |
|-------+---------+--------+---------|
| Database | OceanBase | Ant/Alibaba | MulanPubL-2.0 |
| Database | openGauss | Huawei | MulanPubL-2.0 |
| Messaging | RocketMQ | Alibaba | Apache-2.0 |
| Service mesh | MOSN | Ant | Apache-2.0 |
| Service registry | Nacos | Alibaba | Apache-2.0 |
| RPC | SOFARPC | Ant | Apache-2.0 |
| RPC | Kitex | ByteDance | Apache-2.0 |
| Enterprise Linux | openEuler | Huawei | GPL |
| Consensus | SOFAJRaft | Ant | Apache-2.0 |
| ML framework | PaddlePaddle | Baidu | Apache-2.0 |
| ML framework | MindSpore | Huawei | Apache-2.0 |

India has no equivalent inventory. That is not an omission in this essay; it is
the finding.

* 5. Depth at a Glance
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: depth
:END:

The same gap, scored layer by layer. The values are the author's judgement,
mid-2026: 0 = none, 1 = shallow, 2–3 = deep.

| Layer | USA | China | India |
|-------+-----+-------+-------|
| OS / kernel | 3 | 2 | 0 |
| Relational DB | 3 | 3 | 1 |
| Message queue | 3 | 3 | 0 |
| RPC | 3 | 3 | 1 |
| Service mesh | 3 | 3 | 0 |
| Registry | 3 | 3 | 0 |
| Consensus | 3 | 2 | 0 |
| Crypto / TLS | 3 | 2 | 0 |
| ML framework | 3 | 3 | 1 |
| Graph DB | 3 | 2 | 0 |

India's column is near-empty. Everything else in this essay explains why.

* 6. The Top 15 Foundational Projects
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: fifteen
:END:

To explain it, first establish how foundational software actually gets built —
not by assertion, but from the cases. Here are fifteen of the most load-bearing
foundational projects in use today, each classified by how it was actually
built.[fn:6] The mechanism numbers are defined in [[#mechanisms][§7]].

| Software | How it was built | Mech. |
|----------+------------------+-------|
| SQLite | one person (Hipp), Navy contract, then public domain | 1 |
| Linux | a student's hobby, then thousands of hands | 1 → 2 |
| Git | Torvalds, ~2 weeks, after BitKeeper's licence was pulled | 1 + 5 |
| Nginx | Sysoev, solo, against Rambler's C10K production wall | 1 + 5 |
| Redis | Sanfilippo, for his startup, when MySQL couldn't keep up | 1 + 5 |
| OpenSSL | SSLeay (two people) → community | 1 → 2 |
| Apache httpd | a group patching abandoned NCSA code | 2 |
| PostgreSQL | a Berkeley research project → community | 3 → 2 |
| Kubernetes | Google externalising Borg | 3 → 2 |
| LLVM | university research (Lattner) → Apple product need | 3 (+1) |
| BSD / TCP-IP | Berkeley under DARPA contract | 3 (direct) |
| The Web | a physicist at CERN needing to share documents | 4 |
| R | statisticians needing a teaching tool | 4 |
| OceanBase | Ant, when Oracle couldn't survive Alipay's load | 5 + 3 |
| Hadoop | two builders on Google's papers, then Yahoo's backing | 5 + 3 |

* 7. The Five Mechanisms
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: mechanisms
:END:

** 7.1 The Taxonomy
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: taxonomy
:END:

Five mechanisms recur across the fifteen. The taxonomy is a model, not a
peer-reviewed framework.

| # | Mechanism | What it is | Examples |
|---+-----------+------------+----------|
| 1 | Lone obsessive | one person rebuilds a tool judged wrong at the root | SQLite, Git, Gitea |
| 2 | Mass community | many hands, a shared standard, no single owner | Linux, PostgreSQL, Kubernetes |
| 3 | Target-bound backing | an agency commissions a named deliverable for a real user | DARPA, the 863 Programme |
| 4 | Cross-domain carry | a domain expert builds because no adequate tool exists | CERN (the Web), R |
| 5 | Forcing function | a scale problem that refuses the workaround | OceanBase, Spanner |

Two drivers dominate the others: /passion/ (1) and /need/ (5). Count the fifteen
by mechanism and the distribution is the argument — projects fire several, so the
counts sum past fifteen.

| Mechanism | Count (of 15) |
|-----------+---------------|
| 1 · Lone obsessive | 7 |
| 5 · Forcing function | 6 |
| 3 · Target-bound backing | 6 |
| 2 · Mass community | 5 |
| 4 · Cross-domain carry | 2 |
| Elite teaching institution | 0 |
| State, for a captive user | 0 |

The lone obsessive and the forcing function drive most of the fifteen, usually
together, often with institutional backing underneath. Cross-domain carry accounts
for two — CERN and R are famous precisely because so few others did it. And the
bottom two cells are /empty/: not one of the fifteen came from an elite teaching
institution building software as its mission, or from a state programme aimed at a
captive user. Those two empty cells are exactly where India's institutions sit.

** 7.2 The Mechanisms in China
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: mech-china
:END:

| Project | Forcing function | Mech. |
|---------+------------------+-------|
| OceanBase (Ant) | Oracle could not survive Singles'-Day load; later took the TPC-C record[fn:7] | 5 + 3 |
| RocketMQ (Alibaba) | ActiveMQ's IO collapsed as queues grew; donated to Apache[fn:8] | 5 → 2 |
| openEuler (Huawei) | US export restrictions turned RHEL into a liability | 3 + 5 |
| openGauss (Huawei) | the same pressure one layer up; a PostgreSQL-derived bank database | 3 + 5 |
| MOSN (Ant) | Envoy could not carry Ant's financial-grade extensions | 5 + 3 |
| Nacos (Alibaba) | registry beyond Consul/etcd; now used outside China | 5 → 2 |
| Kitex / Hertz (ByteDance) | TikTok scale demanded Go; Apache-2.0 to signal global intent | 5 + 1 |
| Monoio (ByteDance) | "Tokio is wrong at the architecture level"; a Rust runtime on io_uring | 1 + 5 |
| TiDB (PingCAP) | three engineers on Google's Spanner paper; now CNCF | 4 + 2 |
| Gitea (individual) | one developer, 2014, built for love — the pure iconoclast | 1 |

** 7.3 The Mechanisms in India
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: mech-india
:END:

| Project | What fired it | Mech. |
|---------+---------------+-------|
| MOSIP | a real external user — a government with no identity stack | 5 |
| Frappe | a lone builder; no adequate open ERP for small business | 1 |
| FLOSS/fund (Zerodha) | a private firm seeding the commons on principle | 2 |
| Deluge (Zoho) | built foundationally on principle, before scale forced it | 3 |
| Drove (PhonePe) | scale broke existing tools; open-sourced to share | 5 + 3 |

The Indian list runs to five lines against China's ten, and four of the five are
single firms acting alone. The asymmetry is not a gap in the research. It is the
result.

* 8. Four Cases
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: cases
:END:

#+begin_export html
<div class="box-positive">
<div class="box-label">MOSIP — the one clean foundational export</div>
<p>
<strong>What:</strong> a modular open-source identity platform, the reference
implementation of Aadhaar's principles, built from 2018 at IIIT-Bangalore.
<strong>Mechanism 5</strong> — a real external user, a government with no identity
stack, pulling the software into the open. <strong>Scale:</strong> ~26 country
engagements and ~130 million IDs generated by 2025. <strong>Caveat:</strong> MOSIP
itself runs on AWS — even this export sits on someone else's cloud.
<strong>Significance:</strong> proof India can build globally adopted foundational
software when a genuine forcing function exists.
</p>
</div>
<div class="box-positive">
<div class="box-label">Frappe — the one framework of consequence</div>
<p>
<strong>What:</strong> an application framework (the sense in which Django and
Rails are foundational); ERPNext is built on it. <strong>Origin:</strong> 2009,
GPL. <strong>Mechanism 1</strong> — a lone builder, because no adequate open ERP
existed for small business. <strong>Scale:</strong> a community in the tens of
thousands. <strong>Significance:</strong> the lone-obsessive path that produces
most of the world's foundations, fired for once at home.
</p>
</div>
<div class="box-positive">
<div class="box-label">Zerodha — the firm that funds the commons</div>
<p>
<strong>What:</strong> a brokerage that also builds and funds open source —
Listmonk (AGPL, used globally), DungBeetle, kaf-relay. <strong>FLOSS/fund</strong>
(Oct 2024) commits US$1M a year to global open source, the first round including
US$100,000 to OpenSSL; it co-founded FOSS United. <strong>Mechanism 2</strong> — a
private firm building the community machinery on principle, not because a balance
sheet demanded it. <strong>Significance:</strong> the connective tissue India most
lacks, seeded deliberately.
</p>
</div>
<div class="box-positive">
<div class="box-label">PhonePe / Drove — built, opened, un-adopted</div>
<p>
<strong>What:</strong> a container orchestrator (Drove) and bare-metal provisioner
(Nimbus), open-sourced. <strong>How:</strong> PhonePe's scale — ~350,000 cores,
3 PB, ~7s VM creation — broke existing tools, so it built its own.
<strong>Mechanism 5 + 3.</strong> <strong>Status:</strong> in production, largely
un-adopted outside PhonePe. <strong>Significance:</strong> proof that Indian firms
at scale can build the floor — and that building it is not enough without
<a href="#mechanisms">mechanism 2</a>.
</p>
</div>
#+end_export

* 9. Why Have We Failed?
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: why
:END:

#+begin_quote
The three sub-sections that follow are analytical provocations, not findings drawn
from survey data or econometrics. They are offered to test the hypothesis, not to
assert it as fact. /(Inferred throughout.)/
#+end_quote

** 9.1 The Iconoclasts Exist — They Are Building Apps
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: madmen
:END:

India does not lack obsessive engineers. It lacks obsessive engineers /building
foundations/. The incentive structure pulls every able builder toward the next
fintech app, the next SaaS product, the next services contract — the application
layer, where the money is. The talent is real; its direction is the problem.

** 9.2 Those Who Would Build Foundations Are Not Supported
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: support
:END:

The enabling conditions are missing across the board: no patient capital for
foundational work; no institutional backing for a "build a database" project; no
neutral governance, in the way the Apache Foundation gave Chinese projects a
trusted home; and no community machinery to sustain a project past its first
commit. The rare successes — Zerodha, MOSIP — happened /despite/ the system, not
because of it.

** 9.3 The Institutions See Only the Immediate
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: myopia
:END:

The Indian technology economy runs on quarterly billing cycles, not decadal
horizons. The services giants are organised around billable hours, not R&D;[fn:28]
startups answer to VCs who reward growth velocity, not engineering depth;
government works in five-year plans, not twenty-year roadmaps. China's 863
Programme funded ten- to fifteen-year horizons; India's STPI had a comparable
horizon and pointed it at services export.

** 9.4 What the Governments Did
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: governments
:END:

The contrast in state action is the cleanest in the essay.

| | China | India |
|-+-------+-------|
| Research programme | 863 (1986): outcome-based funding, named deliverables, real users[fn:5] | — |
| Commercialisation bridge | Torch (1988): lab-to-industry | STPI (1991): tax breaks, bandwidth, parks — pointed at services export |
| Substitution mandate | IOE: remove IBM/Oracle/EMC | — |
| Indigenous OS | (emerged from firms under pressure) | BOSS: a Linux re-spin, no adoption, no feedback loop |
| Result | OceanBase, openEuler, RocketMQ | a services industry, and no foundational stack |

The forms were not absent in India — DRDO is a mission-funded agency like DARPA,
STPI an adoption bridge like Torch. The targeting was wrong: DRDO aimed at defence
hardware for a single captive user, STPI at labour-cost arbitrage. /(See also the
[[https://gagan-p.github.io/articles-gp/articles/orange-economy-critique.html][Orange
Economy critique]].)/

* 10. What Can Be Done
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: path
:END:

** 10.1 Stop Asking the Elite Institutions
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: scrap
:END:

India's reflex is to ask its elite institutions, big corporates, and government to
deliver the breakthrough together. The [[#fifteen][cases]] say this cannot work,
because the elite-institution model is aligned against four of the five
mechanisms:

- /Mechanism 1/ — it optimises for individual escape velocity, not obsession; the
  graduate who could build a database leaves, abroad or to the app layer.
- /Mechanism 2/ — it is small and insular; it does not produce the distributed
  communities that build Linux or Kubernetes.
- /Mechanism 3/ — its funding is grant-based, not the outcome-based "deliver this
  capability" of DARPA or 863.
- /Mechanism 4/ — its silos keep the domain expert and the computing team apart, so
  the scientist-programmer never emerges.
- /Mechanism 5/ — it faces no production forcing function; no student meets a
  Singles'-Day problem.

Asking it to produce foundations is asking it to do what it is structurally built
not to do.

** 10.2 Build Clusters With a Real Problem
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: clusters
:END:

The configuration that fits is the opposite: clusters of small firms with a real,
shared, unsolved problem and no budget to evade it, paired with a local
polytechnic. Read against the [[#mechanisms][mechanisms]], it instantiates four of
the five — the problem refuses the workaround at the cluster's price point (5);
the polytechnic supplies builders not on an escape trajectory (1); the firms are
the domain experts and the students the computing carry (4); and because no market
is large enough to interest a proprietary vendor, whatever gets built is open by
default (2).

| Cluster | The problem | What a solution looks like |
|---------+-------------+----------------------------|
| Garment (Tiruppur) | logistics over mixed-script addresses | route optimisation with Tamil/English address parsing |
| Mining-transport hub | truck scheduling, load tracking | a small datastore with a plain-text entry interface |
| Agriculture (mandi) | price discovery, quality grading | a mobile-first datastore with offline sync |
| Small-town retail | inventory, billing, credit | a lightweight ERP with an Indian-language UI |

Kerala ran a version of this by accident: a budget-driven decision to put
open-source software in schools produced, two decades on, a disproportionate share
of India's foundational contributors — the Malayalam computing community, its
fonts and morphological tools. The forcing function was poverty, not policy.

* 11. Where to Point a Ten-Year Bet
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: tenyear
:END:

A critique that ends at "build clusters" is weaker than one that names the target.
Leadership is not won by chasing a layer the US and China already own — that is how
one becomes a late tenant again. The test for a defensible target is one clause or
the other: the layer is /being rewritten now/, so incumbency is open; or it is
/structurally Indian/, so the forcing function is real, local, and un-poachable by
any foreign firm. Five candidates, ranked against that test.

| Rank | Target | Being rewritten? | Structurally Indian? | Crowding risk | Verdict |
|------+--------+------------------+----------------------+---------------+---------|
| 1 | Indic-language computing infrastructure — tokenizers, morphology engines, fonts, speech | yes (LLM era) | yes (22 scripts, a billion users) | low (foreign firms cover only Hindi) | strongest |
| 2 | DPI as foundational software — the open reference stack beneath UPI/ONDC/Aadhaar | partly | yes (India leads the protocol) | low (no trusted sovereign vendor) | strong |
| 3 | Privacy-preserving / confidential compute | yes | partly (DPDPA, RBI localisation) | medium | plausible |
| 4 | Earth-observation & agri data pipelines | no | partly (ISRO data, local crops) | low | niche |
| 5 | Post-transformer inference runtime | yes (wide open) | no | high (US/China racing) | late tenant |

The ranking follows the test mechanically. The inference runtime (5) has the
highest upside and the most open floor, but fails the second clause — it is not
structurally Indian, and the US and China are already racing, so India would arrive
late to a contested layer yet again. Earth observation (4) is genuinely
uncontested but narrow. Confidential compute (3) has a real domestic forcing
function in data-localisation law but no special Indian advantage. The top two are
the only candidates that pass /both/ a real moat and a real forcing function.

** The Winner: Indic-Language Computing Infrastructure
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: winner
:END:

The bet is not "an Indian ChatGPT" — that is application software, the tenant's
move. The bet is the /foundational layer beneath every Indic-language model/: the
tokenizer, the morphological analyser, the script-shaping and font stack, the
speech front-end, the evaluation harness. It passes the test on both clauses at
once, which no other candidate does.

- /Being rewritten now./ The LLM era reset the entire language stack. Incumbency
  is open because the incumbents barely showed up: Llama 3.1, Cohere Command R, and
  Aya 23 each cover only Hindi among the Indic languages, and general-purpose
  tokenizers over-fragment Indic scripts — a measured "token fertility" penalty
  that makes every Indic model slower and costlier to run than its English
  equivalent.[fn:32] The layer is being built from scratch right now, by whoever
  builds it first.
- /Structurally Indian, and un-poachable./ Twenty-two scheduled languages across
  multiple script families, agglutinative morphology, a billion users — this is
  [[#mechanisms][mechanism 5]] with a permanent moat. No US or Chinese firm will
  ever build it properly, because the forcing function is not theirs; the cost of
  bad Indic tokenisation lands on Indian users, not on Mountain View. That is the
  rare combination the rest of the essay says India lacks: a foundational problem
  that /only India is forced to solve./

The raw material already exists but is fragmented and under-resourced — exactly the
state §3 describes. AI4Bharat at IIT Madras has shipped IndicTrans2 (all 22
scheduled languages, a 230M-pair parallel corpus), iNLTK, and the Indic LLM-Arena
benchmark; Krutrim and others have published Indic-specific tokenizers
(IndicSuperTokenizer) that beat the general-purpose ones on fertility.[fn:33] The
pieces are scattered across labs and startups, none owning the whole floor. The
ten-year move is consolidation, not invention: take the [[#clusters][cluster
model]] from §10.2 — polytechnics and language departments as the domain experts,
a real billion-user forcing function, open-by-default because no proprietary vendor
will serve a fragmented low-margin market — and aim it at a single, governed,
permissively licensed Indic-language /infrastructure/ layer that every downstream
model is forced to depend on. Whoever owns that tokenizer owns a floor under the
entire Indian AI economy. It is the one foundational layer India is structurally
advantaged to win, and the one no one will hand it.

* Close
:PROPERTIES:
:CUSTOM_ID: close
:END:

India's software success is real, and it is the success of a tenant. Forty years
of services and arbitrage produced wealth and reputation — and not the capacity to
build the floor, because arbitrage and foundations are made by opposite conditions
and India built only the first set. China proves the second set can be assembled;
the [[#fifteen][fifteen cases]] show what assembles it; the [[#india-list][short
Indian list]] shows how rarely the same engine fires at home.

India does not lack people — it has supplied the world's foundational software with
its people for decades. It lacks the /conditions/ under which those people do that
work /at home/. Jugaad — the celebrated knack for the workaround — is the antonym
of the disposition that builds floors, which begins instead with the refusal to
patch. The institution India trusts most is the one least suited to the task. The
capacity is a choice about conditions, not a fact about talent — and the choice is
still open.

/(See also an earlier treatment:
[[https://gagan-p.github.io/articles-gp/articles/software_oss_Ind_Chn.html][Renting
vs. Owning the Stack]].)/

#+begin_quote
Editor's note. A contested thesis, with its interpretive leaps marked.
Quantitative claims are sourced and current to mid-2026; market values move daily
and the premium argument is built to hold at the order-of-magnitude level. Scores
in §5 are judgements. Corrections welcome.
#+end_quote

