[fn:31] Alibaba rose ~70–84% in 2025, re-rated as an AI-and-cloud infrastructure
company on the strength of Alibaba Cloud (>30% YoY growth) and the Qwen models;
the broader Chinese tech complex (Alibaba, Tencent) outperformed on the same AI
wave (Barchart/Yahoo Finance; The Motley Fool, Dec 2025). The stock's ~20–27%
pullback in 2026 is a deliberate consequence of a US$52–56B AI-infrastructure capex
commitment that turned free cash flow negative on purpose, not a reversal of the
re-rating (CNBC; Barchart, 2026) — the opposite of India's decline: investing
deeper into the floor rather than being displaced from it.

[fn:32] Indic LLM coverage and tokenisation: Llama 3.1 supports Hindi as its only
Indic language; Cohere Command R and Aya 23 likewise cover only Hindi among Indic
languages ("Analysis of Indic Language Capabilities in LLMs," arXiv:2501.13912,
2025). General-purpose tokenizers over-fragment Indic scripts, raising "token
fertility" (sub-words per word) and with it inference cost ("Multilingual
Tokenization through the Lens of Indian Languages," arXiv:2506.17789, 2025).

[fn:33] Indic-language infrastructure: AI4Bharat (IIT Madras) — IndicTrans2 across
all 22 scheduled languages with a 230M-pair Bharat Parallel Corpus (Gala et al.,
2023), iNLTK (Arora, 2020), Indic LLM-Arena (2025); Krutrim's tokenizer
(arXiv:2407.12481) and IndicSuperTokenizer (2025) report state-of-the-art fertility
on Indic scripts. The work is real but fragmented across labs and startups.

